CRIME
Shell company
Jim Waterson on the mafiosos using snails to dodge millions in taxes.
The snail farmer of London, his mafia friends, and a =C2=A320m vendetta aga=
inst the taxman [ https://substack.com/redirect/de918a0c-2c06-4a69-9164-faf=
5d8c62762?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3=
ys ]
=E2=80=94Jim Waterson  in London Centric =20
It is a drizzly October afternoon and I am sitting in a rural Lancashire pu=
b drinking pints of Moretti with London=E2=80=99s leading snail farmer and =
a convicted member of the Naples mafia. We=E2=80=99re discussing the best w=
ay to stop a mollusc orgy.
The farmer, a 79-year-old former shoe salesman called Terry Ball who has ma=
de and lost multiple fortunes, has been cheerfully telling me in great deta=
il for several hours about how he was inspired by former Conservative minis=
ter Michael Gove to use snails to cheat local councils out of tens of milli=
ons of pounds in taxes.
His method is simple. First, he sets up shell companies that breed snails i=
n empty office blocks. Then he claims that the office block is legally, aga=
inst all indications to the contrary, a farm, and therefore exempt from pay=
ing taxes.
=E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re sexy things,=E2=80=9D chuckles Ball in a broad Bla=
ckburn accent, describing the speed with which two snails can incestuously =
multiply into dozens of specimens if they=E2=80=99re left alone in a box fo=
r a few weeks. Snails love group sex and cannibalism, he warns.
As the conversation drifts away from snail breeding he describes personal c=
onnections to a very prominent member of the House of Commons, his years hi=
ding Italian mafia killers while they were on the run, and the potential ma=
rket for snail salami.
Almost everything he tells me seems improbable, yet everything I could late=
r verify checks out. I=E2=80=99ve got little reason to doubt the rest.
We=E2=80=99re drinking with =E2=80=9CJoseph=E2=80=9D, a snail farm employee=
=2E An hour earlier I=E2=80=99d seen him u=
sing a cleaver to chop up lettuce t=
o feed thousands of the animals. They=E2=80=99re then shipped out to premis=
es across the country, including four big snail farms they=E2=80=99re curre=
ntly running in London. Taking out his phone, Ball shows off pictures of an=
other man, =E2=80=9Cmy mafia boss friend=E2=80=9D, posing with the legendar=
y Napoli footballer Diego Maradona in the 1980s.
=E2=80=9CJoseph=E2=80=9D, who speaks with an unusual Italian-Lancastrian ac=
cent, turns out to be a man called Giuseppe from Naples. In a very matter-o=
f-fact manner Giuseppe explains how he previously spent four years inside p=
rison because a former friend, a convicted mafia murderer, turned into an i=
nformant and helped the Italian authorities convict his former criminal col=
leagues.
Ball says he has employed Giuseppe to look after his tax-dodging snails as =
a thank-you. Giuseppe once warned him not to travel to Italy, at a time whe=
n the snail magnate might have been prosecuted due to the confessions of th=
e same informant.
Three hours earlier I knew none of this. I=E2=80=99d turned up unannounced =
at Ball=E2=80=99s snail farm HQ with a faint hope that I might catch a glim=
pse of the man behind one of the most brazen tax dodges I=E2=80=99d ever en=
countered in the capital. It=E2=80=99s just the latest part of London Centr=
ic=E2=80=99s ongoing investigations into the financial scams taking place i=
n plain sight across London.
