PHOTOGRAPHY
TRAVEL
Photo exhibit
Madison Huizinga on the weird ubiquity of Instagram =E2=80=9Cmuseums,=E2=80=
=9D places =E2=80=9Cdesigned not for education or even entertainment, but f=
or picture-taking.=E2=80=9D
Dreams Are Just Delusions [ https://substack.com/redirect/4406e6d8-50f1-416=
9-a491-a92b213a754a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9=
ecHmePkbA3ys ]
=E2=80=94Madison Huizinga  in Cafe Hysteria =20
At the mouth of the Sunset Junction in Los Angeles=E2=80=94at the intersect=
ion of Sunset and Hyperion, to be exact=E2=80=94you=E2=80=99ll find a line =
of people baking in the 3 PM sun in their cross-body bags and Adidas Stan S=
miths, looping around the Salt & Straw, waiting to have their photo taken. =
They=E2=80=99re waiting in line for the Photo Booth Museum by Photomatica. =
The decor at this establishment emulates a mid-century soda shop, with its =
minimalist serif font, robin=E2=80=99s-egg blue, light wood, and chrome fin=
ishes. The space contains several models of vintage photo booths, including=
 a Photo-Me Model 17, =E2=80=9Cconstructed with stainless steel, marine-gra=
de wood, and just the right amount of nostalgia,=E2=80=9D according to the =
website. Photomatica is the brainchild of Doug Ellington, who built his fir=
st photo booth for his own wedding in 2010, the dawn of stomp-clap hipsterd=
om. Today, he and his business partner, Matt Dewalt, are in the business of=
 pop-ups and permanent installations. =E2=80=9COur goal is to spread as muc=
h photo booth love as possible,=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=9CAbout Us=E2=80=9D sec=
tion of the website reads.
The =E2=80=9Cmuseum=E2=80=99s=E2=80=9D LA location deems itself a =E2=80=9C=
hotspot for all things analog,=E2=80=9D which is ironic given its highly po=
stable, ephemeral qualities. Many on TikTok deem it a =E2=80=9Cperfect date=
 spot,=E2=80=9D documenting the whole process=E2=80=94from the line-waiting=
, to the picture-taking, to the printing, to drying the photos with a hair =
dryer=E2=80=94alongside the dreamy black-and-white images themselves. Photo=
matica=E2=80=99s website asserts that photo booth strips offer =E2=80=9Cpro=
of you were here.=E2=80=9D Proof you were where, exactly, is the question. =
Photo booths are common fixtures at movie theaters, bars, arcades, and bowl=
ing alleys, offering a physical token to commemorate a wedding, birthday, a=
nniversary date, or simply a fun evening with friends. Proof you celebrated=
, proof you loved, proof of Life with a capital L. The Photo Booth Museum t=
urns the token into the experience itself, offering proof that you waited i=
n line for said proof.
Major American cities have been plagued by these experiential pop-ups over =
the last decade; the Photo Booth Museum, Museum of Illusions, and infamous =
Museum of Ice Cream are among the most popular ones. Presumably, these exhi=
bits brand themselves as =E2=80=9Cmuseums=E2=80=9D as a way to lure in undi=
scerning tourists via organic and paid search ads. People assume they=E2=80=
=99re purchasing tickets to experience a local fixture. In reality, they=E2=
=80=99re entering a playscape, perfectly lit for Instagram photos, designed=
 not for education or even entertainment, but for picture-taking.
A couple of months ago, my mom tried to buy tickets for our family to visit=
 the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam, clicked the wrong Google link, and purch=
ased tickets to the pop-up =E2=80=9CVan Gogh Immersive Experience,=E2=80=9D=
 which consists of sitting on lawn chairs in a warehouse while images of Va=
n Gogh=E2=80=99s art are projected onto the surrounding walls. The projecti=
ons feature animated versions of the art, the starry night twirling, the su=
nflowers spinning, like something out of an AI-generated Facebook post. All=
 of it artificial, images of images. =E2=80=9CHave you ever dreamt of stepp=
ing into a painting?=E2=80=9D the website asks. =E2=80=9CNow you can.=E2=80=
=9D I helped her get a refund.
